         <abstract>
            <p>Let $D$ be a real function such that $D(z)$ is analytic and $D(z) \neq 0$ for $|z| \leq 1$. Furthermore, put $W(x) = \sqrt{1 - x^2}|D(e^{i\varphi})|^2, x = \cos \varphi, \varphi \in \lbrack 0, \pi\rbrack$, and denote by $p_n(\cdot, W)$ the polynomial which is orthogonal on $\lbrack-1, +1\rbrack$ to $\Bbb{P}_{n - 1} (\Bbb{P}_{n - 1}$ denotes the set of polynomials of degree at most $n - 1$) with respect to $W$. In this paper it is shown that for each sufficiently large $n$ the polynomial $E_{n + 1}(\cdot, W)$ (called the Stieltjes polynomial) of degree $n + 1$ which is orthogonal on $\lbrack-1, + 1\rbrack$ to $\Bbb {P}_n$ with respect to the sign-changing function $p_n(\cdot, W)W$ has $n + 1$ simple zeros in $(-1, 1)$ and that the interpolation quadrature formula (called the Gauss-Kronrod quadrature formula) based on nodes which are the $2n + 1$ zeros of $E_{n + 1}(\cdot, W)p_n(\cdot, W)$ has all weights positive.</p>
          </abstract>
